\begin{abstract}

We propose a formulation of the cosmic censorship hypothesis within the
Hamiltonian Crystal framework, in which spacetime geometry emerges from
a discrete vacuum Hamiltonian defined over a lattice of Fock-space modes.
Spectral gaps in the vacuum Hamiltonian produce bounded curvature,
naturally preventing the formation of singularities. Gravitational collapse
corresponds to large excitations of crystal modes rather than divergent
geometric curvature. The framework yields a finite curvature bound,
a discrete horizon area spectrum, and a modified black hole entropy
formula containing logarithmic corrections. We also explore the possibility
that the vacuum spectral structure follows number-theoretic distributions,
such as prime spectra or Riemann zeros, providing a connection between
quantum gravity and arithmetic structure.

\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}

General relativity predicts the formation of spacetime singularities under
gravitational collapse. The cosmic censorship hypothesis suggests that such
singularities are hidden behind event horizons and therefore cannot be
observed by distant observers.

However, singularities arise within the classical continuum description of
spacetime. If spacetime is instead an emergent structure arising from a
deeper quantum system, the divergence of curvature may be replaced by
bounded spectral behavior.

In this work we explore cosmic censorship within the Hamiltonian Crystal
framework, where spacetime geometry emerges from a discrete Hamiltonian
defined over Fock-space lattice modes.

\section{Hamiltonian Crystal Vacuum}

We assume the vacuum is described by a Hamiltonian

\begin{equation}
H_{\text{crystal}}
=
\sum_{n} \Delta E_n a_n^\dagger a_n + H_{\text{int}}
\end{equation}

where

\begin{itemize}
\item $a_n^\dagger, a_n$ are Fock creation and annihilation operators
\item $\Delta E_n$ are spectral gaps of vacuum modes
\item $H_{\text{int}}$ describes interactions between modes
\end{itemize}

The vacuum ground state is

\begin{equation}
a_n |0\rangle = 0
\end{equation}

and excitations correspond to local energy density.

\section{Spectral Gap Structure}

We assume the vacuum spectral gaps obey

\begin{equation}
\Delta E_n = E_* f(n)
\end{equation}

where $E_*$ is a fundamental energy scale.

Two possible spectral structures are

\subsection{Geometric hierarchy}

\begin{equation}
f(n) = \epsilon^n
\end{equation}

\subsection{Number theoretic spectrum}

\begin{equation}
f(n) = \log p_n
\end{equation}

where $p_n$ is the $n$th prime number.

\section{Emergent Curvature}

Define the local spectral energy density

\begin{equation}
\rho(x) =
\frac{1}{l_c^3}
\sum_n
\Delta E_n
\langle a_n^\dagger a_n \rangle
\end{equation}

where $l_c$ is the lattice spacing.

Using Einstein's equation

\begin{equation}
G_{\mu\nu} = 8\pi G T_{\mu\nu}
\end{equation}

we identify

\begin{equation}
T_{\mu\nu} \sim \rho(x) u_\mu u_\nu
\end{equation}

so curvature is determined by spectral energy.

\section{Curvature Bound}

Assume mode occupation numbers satisfy

\begin{equation}
k_n \le k_{\max}
\end{equation}

The maximum energy density is therefore

\begin{equation}
\rho_{\max}
=
\frac{k_{\max}}{l_c^3}
\sum_n \Delta E_n
\end{equation}

The resulting curvature bound becomes

\begin{equation}
R_{\max} \sim 8\pi G \rho_{\max}
\end{equation}

Since $\rho_{\max}$ is finite, curvature remains finite.

\section{Cosmic Censorship}

A classical singularity corresponds to

\begin{equation}
|R_{\mu\nu\rho\sigma}| \rightarrow \infty
\end{equation}

However in the Hamiltonian crystal

\begin{equation}
R \le R_{\max}
\end{equation}

Therefore singularities cannot form. Cosmic censorship emerges naturally
from spectral boundedness.

\section{Black Hole Formation}

Gravitational collapse corresponds to exciting many lattice modes.

Define total excitation number

\begin{equation}
N = \sum_n k_n
\end{equation}

Total energy becomes

\begin{equation}
E = \sum_n k_n \Delta E_n
\end{equation}

A horizon forms when

\begin{equation}
R_s = \frac{2GE}{c^4}
\end{equation}

\section{Horizon Area Spectrum}

Assume each crystal cell contributes a fundamental area

\begin{equation}
A = N l_c^2
\end{equation}

Thus the horizon area becomes discrete.

\section{Microstate Counting}

The number of ways to distribute $N$ excitations among modes grows
approximately as

\begin{equation}
\Omega(N) \approx
\exp\left(2\sqrt{\alpha N}\right)
\end{equation}

Entropy is

\begin{equation}
S = k_B \ln \Omega
\end{equation}

leading to

\begin{equation}
S \approx 2 k_B \sqrt{\alpha N}
\end{equation}

Using

\begin{equation}
N = \frac{A}{l_c^2}
\end{equation}

gives

\begin{equation}
S \propto \sqrt{A}
\end{equation}

\section{Prime Spectrum Correction}

If the spectral structure follows prime distributions,

\begin{equation}
\Delta E_n \sim \log p_n
\end{equation}

the density of states changes according to the prime number theorem

\begin{equation}
\pi(x) \sim \frac{x}{\log x}
\end{equation}

This modifies the microstate growth to

\begin{equation}
\Omega(E) \sim e^{\beta E}
\end{equation}

which restores area scaling

\begin{equation}
S \propto A
\end{equation}

\section{Modified Black Hole Entropy}

The resulting entropy becomes

\begin{equation}
S =
\frac{k_B A}{4 l_P^2}
+
\eta k_B \log\left(\frac{A}{l_P^2}\right)
\end{equation}

where $\eta$ is a constant of order unity.

\section{Riemann Spectral Operator}

If vacuum modes correspond to Riemann zeros

\begin{equation}
\zeta\left(\frac12 + i\gamma_n\right) = 0
\end{equation}

we may define a Hamiltonian

\begin{equation}
H = \sum_n \gamma_n a_n^\dagger a_n
\end{equation}

In this picture:

\begin{itemize}
\item vacuum spectra correspond to zeta zeros
\item primes determine spectral density
\item geometry emerges from number-theoretic structure
\end{itemize}

\section{Predictions}

The Hamiltonian crystal framework predicts

\begin{itemize}
\item finite curvature inside black holes
\item absence of true singularities
\item discrete horizon area spectrum
\item logarithmic corrections to black hole entropy
\item possible number-theoretic structure in vacuum spectra
\end{itemize}

\section{Conclusion}

The Hamiltonian crystal framework provides a natural mechanism for cosmic
censorship through bounded spectral energy. In this model singularities are
replaced by highly excited but finite vacuum lattice states. The resulting
structure predicts discrete horizon spectra and entropy corrections while
potentially linking quantum gravity to number-theoretic structures such as
prime distributions and Riemann zeros.

